#v(0.8em)
#text(size: 10pt)[
*The idea.* Every one of the 5053 fixed 10-cell polyiamonds (shapes where rotations and reflections are counted as distinct) can be placed, by parity-preserving translation alone, somewhere inside the teal region above. The bounding box of the container is 6 x 10, which sits inside the solver search rectangle of $10 times 10$.
]
#v(0.5em)
#text(size: 10pt)[
*Orientation and parity.* The triangular lattice has two cell orientations: up-pointing and down-pointing. In our $(r, c)$ coordinates, a cell is up-pointing when $(r + c)$ is even and down-pointing when $(r + c)$ is odd. Pure translation (parity-preserving shift) never swaps orientations, so the up- and down-pointing monotriangles count as two distinct fixed 1-iamonds (matching OEIS A001420(1) = 2) -- and the count of fixed $n$-iamonds is $2, 3, 6, 14, 36, 94, 250, 675, 1838, 5053$ for $n = 1$ through $10$.
]
#v(0.5em)
#text(size: 10pt)[
*How it was proved.* For each $n = 1, ..., 10$, a SAT solver with CEGAR connectivity search descended $k -> k - 1$ within the $n times n$ rectangle until it produced a model of size $a_"box"(n)$ and an UNSAT certificate at $a_"box"(n) - 1$. Every proved value is independently cross-checked by two verifiers with disjoint code paths from the main solver: a pure-Python geometric containment verifier and a Glucose-based spanning-arborescence re-optimiser. All three stacks agree on $n = 1..10$.
]
#v(0.5em)
#text(size: 10pt)[
*Conditional reading.* The proved value $a_"box"(n)$ is the minimum container size subject to the container cells fitting inside the $n times n$ rectangle after a parity-preserving translation. Assumption (S) in the paper states that at least one unrestricted minimum container fits inside such a rectangle for every $n$; under (S), $a_"box"(n) = a(n)$ for all $n >= 1$. Every computed optimal container in $n = 1..10$ is consistent with (S), but a general proof is open.
]
#v(0.5em)
#text(size: 10pt)[
*Contrast with the hexagonal grid.* On the hex grid (the sibling problem tracked in oeis-a000217x), the fixed-polyhex container sequence coincides with the triangular numbers $T_n = n(n + 1)/2$ through $n = 7$, giving a clean closed form. On the triangular lattice no such coincidence holds: $a_"box"(1..10) = 2, 4, 6, 9, 12, 17, 22, 27, 31, 39$ does not match any simple closed form, linear recurrence, or known OEIS sequence -- including A024206, which was tentatively conjectured in a prior pass and is falsified term-by-term in the paper.
]